VL  - 48
IS  - 1
SP  - 83
EP  - 117
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/04/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(91)90033-A
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769190033A
AB  - Inference on simultaneous equation models using a Bayesian approach is still far from a routine procedure: serious numerical problems may occur in most practical situations. In this paper a unifying framework is proposed using recent analytical [see Steel (1988)] and well-documented poly-t based methods in order to reduce the dimension of the final Monte Carlo integration. Different integration sequences are examined and the implications for various model and prior assumptions are tabulated. An application to Klein's model I clearly illustrates the computational feasibility and numerical stability of the hybrid method proposed.
