T1  - Empirical models of discrete games
AU  - Bresnahan, Timothy F.
AU  - Reiss, Peter C.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 48
IS  - 1
SP  - 57
EP  - 81
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/04/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(91)90032-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407691900329
AB  - This paper develops econometric models for discrete games. Specifically, we model the payoffs of games where a researcher observes qualitative or censored information about agents' decisions and payoffs. These models extend single-person qualitative choice models introduced by McFadden (1974) and others to multiple-person choice problems. The equations describing players' equilibrium strategies depend on the game's structure and the equilibrium solution concept. We show that one can describe the equilibria of a simultaneous-move Nash game with a linear system of dummy endogenous variables. We also show that sequential-move and cooperative models have different, but related, econometric structures. A series of applied examples address identification and estimation issues. These examples include models of market entry, technology adoption, tax auditing, and cooperative family labor supply.
ER  - 
